The start symbol S has only two productions:

1. S → NT74 NT57  
   NT57 can produce only the single terminal t24.  
   Therefore, any string derived via this rule must end with t24.  
   The given string ends with t69, so this production cannot generate it.

2. S → NT52 NT41  
   NT41 can produce either  
      • the single terminal t54, or  
      • a two-terminal sequence chosen from {t81 t80, t81 t67, t80 t80, t80 t67}.  
   Hence any string derived via this rule must end with t54 or with one of those two-token combinations.  
   The given string ends with … t10 t69, which matches none of them, so this production also cannot generate it.

Since both possible derivations from S are impossible for the provided string, the string is not in the language of the grammar.

No

By analysing the productions we can build the string step-by-step.

1.  The start symbol must take the second alternative  
       S → NT52 NT41  
    because the other alternative would force the string to end with the
    terminal t24, which it doesn’t.

2.  The last two tokens of the string are t80 t80.  
       NT56 → t80 and NT40 → t80  
       NT41 → NT56 NT40  
    So the suffix “t80 t80’’ is produced by NT41 exactly as required by S’s
    second alternative.  All remaining 41 tokens therefore have to be
    generated by NT52.

3.  NT52 has the single production  
       NT52 → NT17 NT17.  
    Hence we have to split the first 41 tokens into two blocks, each produced
    by one NT17.  A natural cut is after the twentieth token:

       first NT17 :  t72 t83 t69 t72 t81 t74 t81 t6 t62 t98  
                     t69 t19 t72 t83 t87 t7 t11 t35 t27 t10

       second NT17:  t69 t87 t61 t35 t87 t35 t69 t61 t69 t75  
                     t72 t11 t35 t19 t10 t87 t69 t35 t69 t35 t87

4.  For each of these blocks NT17 → NT31 NT38 is used.

   a.  In the first block  
         NT31 → NT11 NT24  
         NT11 → t72  
         NT24 → NT71 NT38 with NT71 → t83 and NT38 → t69  
         so NT31 produces t72 t83 t69.  

       The remaining part of the first block is derived with  
         NT38 → NT17 NT21,
         NT17 being built recursively out of NT31 NT38 to cover
         t72 t81 t74 t81 t6 t62 t98 t69 t19 t72 t83 t87 t7,
         and NT21 → NT13 NT71 with  
              NT13 → NT47 NT51  (t11 t35 t27) and NT71 → NT64 (‘t10’).
       Thus the whole first block is produced by the first NT17.

   b.  The second block is handled in the same fashion:  
       NT31 now uses its alternative NT17 NT19 (the final t35),  
       the chain of productions for the inner NT17 again ends with
       an NT38, and the outer NT38 closes with NT21 → t75.  
       In this way the second block is produced by the second NT17.

5.  Having shown
       NT52 ⇒ first-NT17 second-NT17  
       NT41 ⇒ t80 t80  
    the complete derivation
       S ⇒ NT52 NT41 ⇒ (41 terminals) (t80 t80)
    reproduces the given 43-token string exactly.

Hence the string is generated by the grammar.

Yes
